data.content:
## Migration Analysis

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement + ThreadAbortException as control flow

Your code uses `Thread.Abort()` to kill a thread that exceeds a timeout, and `Thread.ResetAbort()` to swallow the abort. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — it simply doesn't work.

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### If work cooperates with cancellation (preferred)

The above has a **critical limitation**: if `work` is CPU-bound and ignores the token, it keeps running in the background after the timeout. For true cancellation, pass the token into the work:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    try
    {
        return Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                   .WaitAsync(cts.Token)
                   .GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller usage:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Fire-and-forget background work** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation doesn't kill the thread. If `work` ignores the token, it runs to completion silently in the background, consuming CPU/memory. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish your timeout from an external cancellation. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` inside work won't respond to cancellation** | Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` so the sleep wakes on cancel. |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If you truly cannot modify `work` to check the token, move it to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. That's the only way to forcibly stop uncooperative code in modern .NET. |

### What was removed and why

| .NET Framework API | Replacement | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` (via timeout) | `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | Cooperative cancellation throws `OperationCanceledException`, not `ThreadAbortException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed entirely | No abort to reset — cancellation is voluntary, not injected |

The fundamental shift: **preemptive → cooperative**. The runtime no longer force-kills threads. Your work code must opt in by checking the `CancellationToken`.
